# poly-app-chromium — hardware-acceleration defaults for the Polycom TC8
# (NXP i.MX8MM: 4x Cortex-A53, etnaviv/Mesa GLES2 GPU, Hantro VPU via
# mainline V4L2 stateless decoders, 800x1280 panel, cage compositor).
#
# Sourced by /usr/bin/chromium (Debian launcher). Flag rationale lives in
# https://github.com/Polycom-Open-Firmware/chromium-a53 README.

# Native Wayland: the TC8 kiosk runs under cage (wlroots, xdg-shell).
CHROMIUM_FLAGS="$CHROMIUM_FLAGS --ozone-platform=wayland"

# V4L2 hardware video decode (Hantro G1: H.264/VP8; G2: HEVC/VP9).
# "AcceleratedVideoDecoder" is the feature string of
# media::kAcceleratedVideoDecodeLinux, which is DISABLED by default in
# non-VAAPI builds (media/base/media_switches.cc, M150). Our build has
# use_v4l2_codec=true + use_vaapi=false, so this single feature turns the
# whole pipeline on. Its companions AcceleratedVideoDecodeLinuxGL and
# AcceleratedVideoDecodeLinuxZeroCopyGL are already default-enabled.
# The stateless-vs-stateful backend needs no flag: Chromium probes the
# driver (Hantro exposes *_SLICE/_FRAME formats => stateless
# V4L2VideoDecoder is selected automatically), and on non-ChromeOS Linux
# it scans plain /dev/video* nodes.
#
# NOTE: --enable-features is last-one-wins. If another chromium.d snippet
# or the kiosk unit adds --enable-features, merge the lists instead.
CHROMIUM_FLAGS="$CHROMIUM_FLAGS --enable-features=AcceleratedVideoDecoder"

# etnaviv is not in Chromium's allowlists; without this the GPU process
# may fall back to software on an unrecognized GL vendor string.
CHROMIUM_FLAGS="$CHROMIUM_FLAGS --ignore-gpu-blocklist"

# GPU rasterization on etnaviv (Debian's default-flags also sets this;
# repeated flags are harmless).
CHROMIUM_FLAGS="$CHROMIUM_FLAGS --enable-gpu-rasterization"

# KNOWN RISK (bench-verify): the Linux GPU-process sandbox may deny
# opening /dev/videoN (V4L2 nodes are not in the desktop sandbox broker
# allowlist the way VAAPI render nodes are). If chrome://media-internals
# shows the decoder failing to open the device, test with
#   --disable-gpu-sandbox
# and if that fixes it, prefer a small broker-allowlist patch in the
# next recipe rev over shipping the sandbox off.

# GL/ANGLE backend: deliberately left on auto-selection for the first
# bench evaluation. If chrome://gpu shows SwiftShader (software) on the
# GC NanoUltra, evaluate in this order and bake the winner here:
#   --use-angle=gles   ANGLE passthrough over native GLES (etnaviv's
#                      native API; preferred if the ES version is enough)
#   --use-angle=gl     ANGLE over desktop GL 2.1 compat
# See README "GL/ANGLE decision" for the trade-offs.
